  "prompt": "Why can't planets be different shapes?",
  "response": "Planets can't be different shapes primarily due to the force of gravity. Gravity pulls matter towards the center of mass, causing an accumulation of mass into a roughly spherical shape. This happens because, for any given volume, a sphere is the most efficient shape to minimize the gravitational potential energy, making it the 'lowest energy state' for a large, self-gravitating mass. \n\nWhen celestial bodies are sufficiently massive, their gravity overcomes the rigidity of the material they're made of, pulling them into a spherical shape. Smaller bodies, like asteroids, can have irregular shapes because their gravitational force isn't strong enough to overcome the material strength and other forces acting on them.\n\nAdditionally, the rotation of a planet can cause it to be slightly flattened at the poles and bulging at the equator due to centrifugal forces, creating an oblate spheroid shape rather than a perfect sphere. But significant deviations from spherical shape are not sustainable for large planetary bodies because of the dominance of gravitational forces.",
